        title: 'The Language Barrier',
        situation: 'A Spanish-speaking family enrolls their 2-year-old daughter. The parents speak very little English. During the enrollment meeting, you notice the father nodding along to everything you say, but when you ask him to repeat back the pickup authorization policy, it is clear he did not understand. He signs all the forms anyway.',
        question: 'What are your obligations, and how do you handle this enrollment?',
        discussion: 'Obtaining a signature on forms a family does not understand is not informed consent — it is a liability and an ethical failure. Cultural competency requires communicating with families in their preferred language. You must pause the enrollment process and arrange for a qualified interpreter — either a bilingual staff member, a community interpreter, or a telephone interpretation service. Do not use the child as an interpreter (this is inappropriate and potentially harmful). Go back through all critical policies — pickup authorization, illness exclusion, emergency contacts, medication policy — and confirm understanding. Translate key documents into Spanish if possible. This family has the right to fully understand the program their child is entering. Document that interpretation was provided.',
        keyTakeaway: 'Families must be able to understand program policies in their preferred language. A signature on a form they did not understand is not valid consent. Use qualified interpreters — never children.',
